    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv from the current directory. For each file, return a compact summary containing: 1) total number of rows, 2) sorted list of unique cmdb_id (components) (limit to top 50 if many), 3) sorted list of unique KPI names (for metric.csv use kpi_name; for trace.csv use trace_name; for log.csv use log_name; for error_logs.csv return no KPI names but show that field exists), and 4) up to the first 10 rows as a sample (include all columns). Keep the output compact and textual. Do not perform any threshold calculations yet."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step loaded all four telemetry files and returned a compact summary. Key observations from that summary: metric.csv is large (27,536 rows) covering 29 components and 359 distinct KPIs; trace.csv has 7,125 rows across 12 components and 72 trace features; log.csv has 506 rows across 7 components and 3 log KPIs; error_logs.csv is empty. Sample rows show timestamps in the files map to datetimes in UTC+8 (e.g., timestamp 1615271400 -> 2021-03-09 06:30:00+08:00). The incident window we must analyze is 2021-03-09 14:30 to 15:00 (UTC+8). Before any anomaly detection we must compute global thresholds on the full series for each component-KPI (per the rules) and only then filter to the incident time window. Next I will ask the Executor to compute global percentiles and identify candidate anomalies in the incident window in a compact, bounded form.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, perform the following steps and keep all intermediate tables cached in kernel variables but only return compact aggregate outputs: 1) Define the incident time window timestamps for 2021-03-09 14:30:00+08 to 2021-03-09 15:00:00+08. (Do NOT convert timestamps yourself; let the code handle timezone conversion.) Provide the numeric start_ts and end_ts used. 2) Consider only component names from the provided possible root cause components list: [\"apache01\",\"apache02\",\"Tomcat01\",\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat03\",\"Tomcat04\",\"MG01\",\"MG02\",\"IG01\",\"IG02\",\"Mysql01\",\"Mysql02\",\"Redis01\",\"Redis02\"]. 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair in metric.csv where cmdb_id is in that list, compute global percentiles using the full available series: P95, P90, P50, P5, plus count, min, max, and mean. 4) Filter metric.csv to rows within the incident window (start_ts <= timestamp <= end_ts). 5) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) candidate from step 3 compute within-window aggregates: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_using_P95 (number of points where value >= global P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (if any), max_value_in_window. 6) Return two compact results: (A) a thresholds table for the candidate (cmdb_id,kpi_name,P95,P5,count_all) limited to top 50 rows sorted by count_all desc; (B) the anomaly candidates in the window: list of up to top 20 rows (cmdb_id,kpi_name,total_points_in_window,anomaly_count_using_P95,earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window,max_value_in_window,global_P95,global_P5) sorted by anomaly_count desc then max_value desc. Keep outputs textual and compact (no full raw series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous execution we computed global thresholds (P95/P5) on the full metric series for all candidate components and then inspected the incident window. Observations: many JVM-Memory_..._HeapMemoryMax and NoHeapMemoryUsed series show P95 identical to max (constant capacity metrics) and thus all window points flagged as >=P95 — these are likely static capacity fields and not causal. Several Tomcat-related KPIs (e.g., Tomcat-Requests_*_MaxTime, Tomcat-Requests_*_ErrorCount, Tomcat-Threads_*_MaxThreads) show every point in the window >= global P95 (31 points), indicating sustained abnormality during the incident window. We should now convert anomaly candidates into concrete 'fault' segments (consecutive anomaly runs) and filter out noise or non-severe constant-series. The next step must: 1) locate consecutive anomaly runs per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) within the incident window where value >= global P95; 2) compute fault segment metrics (start_ts, end_ts, length in points, max_value, anomaly_count, breach_ratio = (max_value - P95)/P95); 3) filter to likely real faults by requiring either sizable breach (breach_ratio > 0.5) or sustained anomalies (anomaly_count >= max(2, 50% of points in-window)); 4) return a compact faults table limited to top 20 rows sorted by severity (breach_ratio desc then anomaly_count desc), plus overall counts and the earliest fault timestamp found. This will let us prioritize which components/KPIs to inspect with traces and logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using cached kernel tables (metric.csv loaded, thresholds table and anomalies_df available), do the following and keep intermediate results cached but return compact outputs: \n1) Using the incident numeric window already defined (start_ts, end_ts), for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) present in anomalies_df, scan the window-rows (ordered by timestamp) and find consecutive runs where value >= global P95 (use the P95 from the thresholds table for that pair). For each run produce one fault segment record with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_start_ts, fault_end_ts, duration_points (number of consecutive minutes), anomaly_count (same as duration_points), total_points_in_window (all points for that pair in window), max_value_in_segment, global_P95, global_P5, breach_ratio = (max_value_in_segment - global_P95)/global_P95 (handle zero P95 safely). \n2) Filter the fault segments to likely real faults by keeping segments that satisfy either: (A) breach_ratio > 0.5 OR (B) anomaly_count >= max(2, 0.5 * total_points_in_window). \n3) Return a compact result: (A) a one-line summary with total number of evaluated candidate (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs and number of fault segments after filtering; (B) the faults table limited to top 20 rows sorted by breach_ratio desc then anomaly_count desc. Include only the columns listed in step 1 for each row. Also return the earliest fault_start_ts among the returned faults (or null if none). Keep output textual and bounded (max 20 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We scanned metric.csv, computed global thresholds per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full series, filtered to the incident window, and extracted consecutive anomaly segments where value >= global P95. The scan produced 20 evaluated candidate (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs and, after applying the filtering rules (breach_ratio>0.5 OR sustained anomalies), 7 fault segments remained. However, most retained segments show breach_ratio == 0.0 because global P95 equals the observed max (these are capacity/constant metrics such as HeapMemoryMax, NoHeapMemoryUsed, some Tomcat MaxTime/MaxThreads/ErrorCount metrics where window values equal historical P95). Such zero-breach segments are likely not revealing a clear causal spike (they may be static or historically-high metrics). Because multiple service-level components appear faulty (IG01/IG02 and Tomcat03/Tomcat04 and Mysql02), and metrics alone are ambiguous, we should use traces next to determine which faulty service is the most downstream faulty service in the call chain. Also note error_logs.csv is empty, so logs may have limited error messages but log.csv is available and will be used after traces. The next step is to analyze trace features for the components identified in the filtered fault segments to find trace-level anomalies (e.g., elevated durations or row_count changes) during the same incident window and return compact top candidates with earliest anomaly timestamps so we can localize the root cause service and occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv and the already-cached incident start_ts and end_ts, do the following and return compact, bounded results: 1) Take the set of unique cmdb_id values from the filtered fault segments cached in kernel (e.g., IG01, IG02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, Mysql02). If that cached set is unavailable, instead restrict to these components: [\"IG01\",\"IG02\",\"Tomcat03\",\"Tomcat04\",\"Mysql02\"]. 2) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in trace.csv where cmdb_id is in that set, compute global percentiles (P95, P90, P50, P5), count_all, min, max, mean using the FULL trace series (do not filter by window before computing thresholds). 3) Then filter trace.csv to rows within the incident window (start_ts <= timestamp <= end_ts). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_using_P95 (value >= global P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (if any), max_value_in_window. 4) Return two compact outputs: (A) thresholds table for these traces: columns (cmdb_id, trace_name, P95, P5, count_all) limited to top 50 rows sorted by count_all desc; (B) anomaly candidates inside the window: up to top 20 rows (cmdb_id, trace_name, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_using_P95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window, max_value_in_window, global_P95, global_P5) sorted by anomaly_count desc then max_value desc. Keep outputs textual and bounded (no full time series). Also return the earliest anomaly timestamp among all returned trace anomalies (or null if none)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We followed the required workflow: computed global thresholds on full series, detected metric anomalies and fault segments, analyzed traces and logs, and produced component-level earliest-breach summaries. Executor's last severe-breach summary shows that a strict numeric SEVERE rule (breach_ratio>0.5 or sustained anomalies) flagged only some trivial metric breaches (e.g., Mysql02’s small NTP offset sustained over 3 points). However, traces and logs indicate a different, more plausible event pattern: an upstream traffic/row_count increase in IG (earliest trace anomaly around 1615271580) followed by Tomcat GC spikes (Tomcat04 earliest GC anomaly 1615271700, Tomcat03 around 1615272000) and elevated Tomcat request metrics. Many metric flags are capacity/static (HeapMemoryMax, MaxThreads, SESSION counters) that equal historical P95 and produce breach_ratio==0.0 and are low-signal. Therefore, we should ignore those static/capacity KPIs and focus on meaningful KPI families: trace row_count/duration, log.gc_pause_max, and CPU/heap usage and request/error KPIs. We need a concise, evidence-based ordering of the earliest meaningful anomalous events (excluding trivial capacity metrics) across metric/trace/log for the candidate components [IG01, IG02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, Mysql02], so we can pick the true root cause component and occurrence time. The next Executor task must extract that ordered list of earliest meaningful anomalies within the incident window, using global thresholds computed on full series.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For components [\"IG01\",\"IG02\",\"Tomcat03\",\"Tomcat04\",\"Mysql02\"] do the following (use cached full-series global thresholds where available; do not recompute thresholds after window filtering):\n1) Define a KPI-name blacklist of likely static/capacity KPIs to exclude: any kpi_name containing any of ['HeapMemoryMax','MaxThreads','SESSION','HeapMemoryMax','MaxTimeRe','_SESSION','HeapMemory'] (case-sensitive substring match). Exclude these KPIs from metric consideration.\n2) From metric.csv consider only metric KPIs (kpi_name) that are NOT blacklisted and that match at least one keyword indicating meaningful operational signals: ['CPU','JVM_CPULoad','SingleCpuUtil','HeapMemoryUsed','ThreadCount','Requests','Request','ErrorCount','row_count','Disk','IO','GC','gc_pause']. From trace.csv consider trace features whose trace_name contains 'row_count' or 'duration' or 'to_' or 'from_'. From log.csv consider log_name in ['log.gc_pause_max','log.row_count','log.error_count'].\n3) For each selected (cmdb_id, KPI, source) compute the global P95 and P5 using the FULL series (cached thresholds if present). Then filter rows to the incident window (start_ts..end_ts). Within the window find the earliest timestamp where the KPI breaches (value >= global_P95 OR value <= global_P5). For that earliest breach output one record with: cmdb_id, source (metric/trace/log), kpi_name, earliest_breach_ts (numeric), value_at_earliest_breach, global_P95, global_P5, breach_type ('high' or 'low'), breach_ratio = (value_at_earliest_breach - global_P95)/global_P95 (handle P95==0 safely), and count_breaches_in_window (number of points in-window meeting the same breach condition for that KPI).\n4) Return the result limited to top 20 rows sorted by earliest_breach_ts ascending (oldest first). Also return the single overall earliest record among them (component/source/kpi with minimum earliest_breach_ts). Keep outputs compact and textual (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The last Executor step applied a KPI blacklist to exclude capacity/static metrics and produced a filtered list of KPI breaches; the top returned breaches are mostly trivial small deviations (breach_ratio near 0) with earliest timestamps at 1615271400. These low-ratio metric breaches are low diagnostic value. From previous steps (trace and log analysis) we observed a more meaningful timeline: trace row_count anomalies (earliest trace anomaly reported earlier at 1615271580) suggest an upstream traffic/row_count surge in IG nodes, and logs show Tomcat GC pause spikes afterwards (Tomcat04 GC first at ~1615271700, Tomcat03 later). This pattern suggests the incident was initiated by increased traffic at the IG layer, which then caused Tomcat GC spikes and elevated request metrics/errors. However, current metric-only earliest breaches are misleading because many are static/capacity KPIs. To finalize root-cause localization we must confirm the earliest meaningful anomaly from trace data (trace-level row_count/duration anomalies) across the candidate components, and return a compact ordered list (oldest first) so we can pick the true initiating component and timestamp. At this point the issue is not resolved because we need the definitive earliest trace anomaly evidence.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv and the cached full-series thresholds (or recompute global P95/P5 on the full trace series if needed), for components [\"IG01\",\"IG02\",\"Tomcat03\",\"Tomcat04\",\"Mysql02\"] do the following and return a compact textual result: 1) Filter trace rows to the incident window (start_ts..end_ts). 2) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global P95 and P5 from the full series, then count how many points in the window have value >= global P95. 3) For each pair with any such breaches, report one row with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_using_P95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window, max_value_in_window, global_P95, global_P5. 4) Return the rows sorted by earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window ascending, limited to top 20 rows. 5) Additionally return the single overall earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window and the corresponding cmdb_id and trace_name (or null if none). Keep outputs compact and textual (no full time series)."
}

